⚠️  COMMON ERROR — UNDER-ESTIMATING A FURNITURE-RICH ROOM
A room that visibly contains MULTIPLE FUNCTIONAL ZONES (e.g. a home
office that ALSO has a lounge corner with sofa+armchairs, a drafting
table, and bookcases on the walls) belongs in the "multi-zone" /
"open-plan" rows of the table above. Do NOT pick the "single-desk
home office" 3.5 × 3.0 m row for such a scene — that is for a tiny
office cubby with one desk and nothing else.

Walk through the math for a multi-zone home office:
  - U-shaped desk + chair envelope:                          ≈ 2.4 × 2.0 m
  - 3-seater sofa + 2 armchairs + coffee table cluster:      ≈ 3.0 × 2.5 m
  - Drafting table + stool:                                  ≈ 1.5 × 1.5 m
  - Wall-side bookcases / filing cabinet on perimeter:       depth ~0.4 m
  - Two main aisles separating the three clusters:           ≥ 0.9 m each
Adding aisles, the absolute minimum is ≈ 7.5 × 5.5 m. A 6.5 × 4.5 m
estimate for that layout is wrong; the furniture would be overlapping.

A.4 SCALE REFERENCE PROCEDURE (do this BEFORE writing estimated_dimensions)
1. Find at least ONE object whose real-world width you know — prefer in
   this priority order, picking whichever is visible AND clearly
   measurable:
     (i)   An interior or exterior door (W 0.85–0.95 m). Most reliable
           because doors are highly standardised across regions and
           styles. ALWAYS use the door as anchor if one is visible.
     (ii)  A queen or king bed (W 1.5 / 1.8 m respectively).
     (iii) A 3-seater sofa (W 2.1 m).
     (iv)  A standard refrigerator (W 0.7 m).
     (v)   An office chair footprint (W 0.6 m).
     (vi)  A dining chair footprint (W 0.45 m).
2. Measure that object's WIDTH in pixels in the top-down image.
3. Compute pixels-per-metre = anchor_pixel_width / anchor_real_width.
4. Measure room interior horizontal pixel span (px_W) and vertical pixel
   span (px_D). Divide each by pixels-per-metre → metric W and D.
5. Round to the nearest 0.5 m — do NOT systematically round up or down,
   either direction is acceptable.
6. CROSS-CHECK A.3: locate the row in A.3 that best matches the visible
   major furniture, and ensure that
     long_edge = max(W, D) ≥ table_long_edge AND
     short_edge = min(W, D) ≥ table_short_edge.
   If either is below, BUMP it up to the table value and note the cue
   that drove the bump in `scale_reference_objects`. Do NOT keep an
   under-sized estimate just because that's what your pixel measurement
   gave you — perspective distortion and image cropping commonly
   compress room sizes in top-down renders.
7. CROSS-CHECK A.0: confirm the W/D orientation matches the image.
8. List your evidence in `scale_reference_objects` as an array of short
   strings, including:
   - the anchor object you used (e.g. "interior door (assumed 0.85 m)")
   - any A.3 row you applied (e.g. "multi-zone home office row → ≥7.5×5.5 m")
   - any other corroborating reference (e.g. "queen bed cross-checked at 1.5 m")

A.5 VISUAL-ARTIFACT WARNINGS
- Many residential / office images use an isometric / 3-quarter top-down
  perspective rather than a strict orthographic view. In that view, the
  FAR side of the room (e.g. the north wall) is visually compressed. Do
  NOT use pixel measurements taken on the far side; prefer reference
  objects sitting in the MIDDLE of the room.
- Wide-angle camera lenses can stretch room corners and make a small
  room look spacious. The opposite is also possible (long-focal-length
  flattening makes a large room look cramped). When in doubt, fall back
  on the A.3 lower-bound table.
- Some renders show a single room with the camera ZOOMED IN tight, so
  the room appears to fill the entire image — but the actual floor area
  is smaller than that aspect ratio suggests because there is no margin
  visible. Always use reference-object measurement, not "the room fills
  the image".
- The image may have rounded corners or a faded border due to image
  processing. These are NOT actual architectural features; treat the
  room as having 4 straight rectangular walls.

A.6 UPPER-BOUND SANITY CHECK (PREVENT OVER-ESTIMATION)
After writing estimated_dimensions, verify it is not absurdly large:
- If your estimate exceeds 14 m × 12 m (≥ 168 m²), check that AT LEAST
  ONE of the following is true:
    (a) You can count ≥ 3 SEPARATE FUNCTIONAL ZONES (e.g. living +
        dining + kitchen + bedroom).
    (b) The image clearly shows a multi-room apartment / loft layout
        with interior partition walls, not a single-room space.
    (c) The long-edge pixel span divided by the typical anchor pixel
        span is ≥ 8.
- If NEITHER of the above holds, you over-estimated. Re-run A.4 with a
  different scale anchor and shrink the estimate. A typical
  single-zone residential room is rarely larger than 8 × 6 m.

==============================================================================
B. FINAL RESIDENTIAL-SPECIFIC VALIDATION CHECK
==============================================================================
Before returning, verify in this order:
1. AXIS CONTRACT (A.0): the FIRST number in estimated_dimensions is W
   (horizontal/east-west); the SECOND is D (vertical/north-south).
   - The orientation matches the image: a visually wider room has W > D,
     a visually taller room has D > W.
   - The pixel ratio sanity check (A.0) holds within ±30 %.
2. LOWER BOUND (A.3): treating the two numbers as long_edge / short_edge,
   each is at or above the row corresponding to the visible major
   furniture mix. A multi-zone room MUST use a multi-zone row, not a
   single-zone row. When in doubt, take the LARGER row.
3. UPPER BOUND (A.6): if your estimate exceeds 14 × 12 m, the conditions
   in A.6 are satisfied; otherwise shrink it.
4. SCALE EVIDENCE: `scale_reference_objects` contains at least one
   anchor entry with the assumed real-world width, plus the A.3 row used.
5. ANCHOR PRIORITY: if a door is visible, you used the door. Otherwise
   you used the next item from A.4's priority list.
